{{For|the homicide victim from Kansas|Murder of Kelsey Smith}}
{{Infobox person | name = Kelsey Shelton Smith-Briggs | image = Kelsey Smith-Briggs.jpg | image_size = 150px | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date|2002|12|28}} | birth_place = [[Oklahoma City, Oklahoma]] | death_date = {{death date and age|2005|10|11|2002|12|28}} | death_place = [[Meeker, Oklahoma|Meeker]], [[Oklahoma]] | death_cause = [[Homicide]] - Blunt force trauma to the abdomen | resting_place = Meeker, Oklahoma | resting_place_coordinates = | residence = | nationality = American | height = | weight = 30 lbs{{citation needed|date=April 2012}} | parents = Lance Briggs and Raye Dawn Smith | relatives = | website = | footnotes = }}
'''Kelsey Shelton Smith-Briggs''' (December 28, 2002 – October 11, 2005) was a [[child abuse]] victim. She died at the home of her [[Mother|biological mother]] Raye Dawn Smith, and her [[stepfather]] Michael Lee Porter. Her death was ruled a [[homicide]].<ref name="TulsaWorld12jan06">[[Tulsa World]] [http://www.tulsaworld.com/news/article.aspx?subjectid=12&articleid=060112_Ne_A11_Toddl6731&archive=yes Toddler's Death Ruled Homicide] retrieved 2009-09-05</ref> Kelsey had been "closely" observed by the [[Oklahoma Department of Human Services]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsok.com/secret-report-rips-dhs/article/3073745/ |first=Nolan|last=Clay |title= Secret Report Rips DHS |work=[[The Oklahoman]] |date=2007-07-01 |accessdate= 2009-09-05}}</ref> from January 2005 up to and including the day of her death.<ref name="OKstateReview032706">Oklahoma Commission on Children and Youth Office of Juvenile System Oversight, Review of Child Death of Kelsey Smith-Briggs March 27, 2006 [http://www.crossroads.odl.state.ok.us/cgi-bin/showfile.exe?CISOROOT=/stgovpub&CISOPTR=3494&filename=3681.pdf#search=%22death.%22 Final Summary] Retrieved 3 September 2009</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/opinion/article.aspx?subjectid=61&articleid=051204_Op_G1_Whofa28461&archive=yes |title= Who failed Kelsey? Toddler's death occurs despite intensive state activity |work=[[Tulsa World]] |date=2005-12-04 |accessdate= 2009-09-05}}</ref>
==Birth and early childhood== Kelsey was born on December 28, 2002, in [[Oklahoma City]], [[Oklahoma]] to [[Divorce|divorced parents]]. She lived with her mother, and maintained contact with her [[paternal]] family. The first two years of her life were uneventful. Before January 2005, no signs of abuse were reported to authorities, nor noticed by family members nor Kelsey's [[day care]] staff.<ref name="NewsOK08jan06" />
==Abuse== From January 2005 to the end of her life, Kelsey had suffered several documented and confirmed incidences of [[child abuse]]. Her injuries included a broken [[collarbone]], [[broken leg]]s, and multiple [[bruises]] and [[Abrasion (medical)|abrasions]] on her [[face]] and [[human body|body]].<ref name="OKstateReview032706"/>
On January 17, 2005, the [[Oklahoma Department of Human Services]] (OKDHS) first confirmed abuse against Kelsey's mother after Kelsey was taken to a local [[emergency room]] with a broken collarbone, multiple bruises and abrasions to Kelsey's [[lower back]], [[buttocks]], and [[thigh]]s.<ref name="OKstateReview032706" />
In April 2005, both of Kelsey's legs were broken. Medical examiners determined these were [[spiral fracture]]s in different stages of healing and were caused by child abuse. After this incident, Kelsey was taken into OKDHS (State's) custody.<ref name="OKstateReview032706" />
On June 15, 2005, Kelsey was placed into the home of biological mother Raye Dawn Smith and stepfather Michael Lee Porter by [[Judge|Associate District Judge]] Craig Key, against an OKDHS recommendation. The judge stated that the abuser was "unknown".<ref name="NewsOK08jan06">''[[The Oklahoman]]'' [http://newsok.com/article/1727132/?template=news/main A broken life: The brief and tragic story of Kelsey Smith-Briggs] retrieved 2009-09-06</ref><ref>Oklahoma Commission on Children and Youth Office of Juvenile System Oversight, Review of Child Death of Kelsey Smith-Briggs Addendum #1 - Court Proceedings of June 15 and June 16, 2005 [http://www.crossroads.odl.state.ok.us/cgi-bin/showfile.exe?CISOROOT=/stgovpub&CISOPTR=3494&filename=3681.pdf#search=%22death.%22 Addendum #1] Retrieved 3 September 2009</ref>
==Death== Kelsey Shelton Smith-Briggs died on October 11, 2005, at the home of her mother, Raye Dawn Smith, and her stepfather, Michael Lee Porter in [[Meeker, Oklahoma]]. Her death was ruled a [[homicide]] from [[blunt force trauma]] to the [[abdomen]].<ref name="TulsaWorld12jan06"/>
==Trial, verdict and sentences== '''Michael Lee Porter''' (stepfather) was charged with [[sexual assault]] and [[first-degree murder]], but in February 2007 he pleaded guilty to enabling child abuse and was sentenced to 30 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsok.com/stepfather-gets-30-years-in-toddlers-death/article/3007900 |title= Stepfather gets 30 years in toddler's death |work=[[The Oklahoman]] |date=2007-02-02 |accessdate= 2009-09-05}}</ref>
'''Raye Dawn Smith''' (biological mother) was convicted on July 18, 2007 of enabling child abuse and was sentenced to 27 years in prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsok.com/mom-found-guilty-jury-hands-down-27-year-prison-term/article/3086520 |first=Nolan|last=Clay |title= Mom found guilty; jury hands down 27-year prison term |work=[[The Oklahoman]] |date=2007-07-19 |accessdate= 2009-09-05}}</ref> She was denied her request for appeal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.poncacitynews.com/templates/298403401614351.bsp |title=District Judge Rules on New Trial for Smith |date=October 10, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719164845/http://www.poncacitynews.com/templates/298403401614351.bsp |archivedate=2011-07-19 |df= }}</ref>
==Kelsey Smith-Briggs Child Protection Reform Act== In March 2006, the [[Oklahoma Legislature|Oklahoma state legislature]] passed the '''Kelsey Smith-Briggs Child Protection Reform Act''' to reform the way courts and the Oklahoma Department of Human Services (OKDHS) handle cases related to child abuse and neglect.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oksenate.org/news/press_releases/press_releases_2006/pr20060426g.html |title=Senate Approves Kelsey’s Law |work=[[Oklahoma State Senate]] Communications Division |date=2006-04-26 |accessdate=2009-09-06 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727142101/http://www.oksenate.org/news/press_releases/press_releases_2006/pr20060426g.html |archivedate=2011-07-27 |df= }}</ref> The bill's co-author, Senator [[Harry Coates]], presented the measure in committee.
